Training dataset has around 80 variables including one target variable SalePrice.Missing values are present in dataset. Variables like MSSubclass, Overall Qual etc are readed as ‘int’ instead of factors by R. ####Data Preprocessing #####Missing value treatment

percentage_na<-function(x){               
  result<-(round(sum(is.na(x))/length(x),2))*100
  return(result)
}
Variable_na_perc<-sapply(test,percentage_na)
Variable_na_perc<-Variable_na_perc[Variable_na_perc>0]
barchart(sort(Variable_na_perc,decreasing = TRUE),xlab="missing value % ")

Plotting the missing value percentage for variables.From the graph above PoolQC, MiscFeature, Alley, Fence and FireplaceQu have more than 50% missing value

#Removing the variables from the dataset which have more than 50% missing values
train_1<-train%>%select(-PoolQC,-MiscFeature,-Alley,-Fence,-FireplaceQu)
#-PoolQC,-MiscFeature,-Alley,-Fence,-FireplaceQu
#Missing value treatment for LotFrontage
#Replacing missing values of lot frontage with median lotfrontage under the neighborhood it falls
lot.by.nbr<-train_1[,c('Neighborhood','LotFrontage')]%>%group_by(Neighborhood)%>%summarise(median=median(LotFrontage,na.rm=TRUE))
idx=which(is.na(train_1$LotFrontage))
for(i in idx){
  lot.median<-lot.by.nbr[lot.by.nbr==as.character(train_1$Neighborhood[i]),'median']
  train_1[i,'LotFrontage']<-lot.median[[1]]
}
#removing rows which have missing value in it
train_treated1<-na.omit(train_1)

Feature creation

variables like year built,year remodeled and yearGrgbuilt are changed into yrs_old_actual,yrs_old_remodel,yrs_garage_old, reason behind this modification is to change the nature from discrete to continous variables

train_treated1<-train_treated1%>%mutate(yrold.actual=YrSold-YearBuilt,yrold.remodel=YrSold-YearRemodAdd,grg.old=YrSold-GarageYrBlt)
train_treated1<-train_treated1%>%select(-YrSold,-YearBuilt,-YearRemodAdd,-GarageYrBlt)

Changing data types from numeric to factor

chng_datatype<-function(x){
  for (i in names(x)){
    if((is.numeric(x[[i]])) & ((length(unique(x[[i]]))/length(x[[i]]))<=0.10)){
      x[[i]]=as.factor(x[[i]])
      
    }
    
  }
  return(x)
}
train_treated2<-chng_datatype(train_treated1)

#ANOVA test to check for Salesprice disparity within categorical variables
name<-c()
val<-c()
for(i in names(train_qual[,1:ncol(train_qual)-1])){
  sm<-summary(lm(data = train_qual,SalesPrice~train_qual[[i]]))
  pval<-log(1/pf(sm$fstatistic[1],sm$fstatistic[2],sm$fstatistic[3],lower.tail = FALSE))
  name<-c(name,i)
  val<-c(val,pval)
  
} 
final<-as.data.frame(cbind.data.frame(name,val))
final<-final%>%filter(name!="OverallQual")%>%arrange(desc(val))
ggplot(data = final,aes(x=reorder(name,val),y=val))+geom_bar(stat = "identity")+coord_flip()+labs(y='mean',x='Variables')

From the plot above we can observe that some categorcal variables have very high SalePrice disparity as compared to other others.

To check for correlation between SalesPrice and categorical variable and multicollinearity within categorical varibles, categorical variables needs to be transformed into ordinal categorical variables.Transforming into ordinal variables means that each observation has been encoded to it’s appropiate rank

encode_melt<-melt(round(cor(train_qual_encoded,method=c('spearman')),2))

So variables like OverallQual,neighborhood,ExterQual,BsmtQual and KitchenQual has high affect on Saleprice.It is quite similar with the ANOVA results we obtained before
